00:03:25.750 --> 00:03:27.140
and forced to work.

00:03:27.140 --> 00:03:28.800
And most of the cases
they're confined

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:32.090
to work places, in
mines, in quarries,

00:03:32.090 --> 00:03:37.080
at [INAUDIBLE], factories,
workshops, houses, restaurants,

00:03:37.080 --> 00:03:37.640
and so on.

00:03:41.540 --> 00:03:44.100
Children are sold and
bought like animals.

00:03:47.080 --> 00:03:49.560
If you allow, I will
tell you a short story.

00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:52.690
Some years ago,
we were organizing

00:03:52.690 --> 00:03:56.460
a march against
child trafficking

00:03:56.460 --> 00:04:00.320
for forced labor or slavery,
the South Asian march,

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:04.470
involving India, Pakistan,
and Nepali children.

00:04:04.470 --> 00:04:08.470
And after the day long
awareness activities,

00:04:08.470 --> 00:04:13.170
we were just relaxing
after dinner,

00:04:13.170 --> 00:04:15.420
and I saw that a
group of children

00:04:15.420 --> 00:04:18.670
were sitting and talking among
each other-- Indian, Pakistani,

00:04:18.670 --> 00:04:21.740
Nepali, Bangladeshi.

00:04:21.740 --> 00:04:24.690
And one of them
asked to other, that

00:04:24.690 --> 00:04:27.630
do you have any idea how much
money you have been sold for?

00:04:30.490 --> 00:04:37.280
A girl said, I can't recall,
but maybe 5,000 rupees.

00:04:37.280 --> 00:04:40.560
That is something
about $80 or so.

00:04:43.550 --> 00:04:50.130
Then two other children
replied, oh, we

00:04:50.130 --> 00:04:55.480
are even lucky that we have been
sold for 7,000 rupees, little

00:04:55.480 --> 00:05:00.730
more, more than $100.

00:05:00.730 --> 00:05:04.745
And then another girl
stood up and said, oh, I

00:05:04.745 --> 00:05:06.700
am even better
because I have been

00:05:06.700 --> 00:05:13.940
sold many years ago
for 10,000 rupees.

00:05:13.940 --> 00:05:16.900
And then one of
the boys stood up

00:05:16.900 --> 00:05:21.010
and asked four of them
that, can you recall,

00:05:21.010 --> 00:05:26.270
do you have any
idea that how much

00:05:26.270 --> 00:05:33.290
is the prize of a buffalo
in your country, or a cow?

00:05:33.290 --> 00:05:36.630
The buffalo was quite
common in South Asia.

00:05:36.630 --> 00:05:40.520
And they looked at each
other, and then one of them

00:05:40.520 --> 00:05:46.100
replied, maybe 50,000 rupees.

00:05:46.100 --> 00:05:47.860
Another said, no, no.

00:05:47.860 --> 00:05:52.030
In my country, it's
about 100,000 rupees.

00:05:52.030 --> 00:05:55.875
I was listening,
and I was in tears.

00:05:59.690 --> 00:06:01.170
What are we talking about?

00:06:01.170 --> 00:06:06.860
These children are comparing
with buffalo and cows.

00:06:06.860 --> 00:06:10.480
A buffalo is sold for
100,000 rupees and a girl

00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:16.920
for 10,000 rupees, 10
times the buffalo's cost.

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:19.655
We are not talking
about medieval slavery.

00:06:19.655 --> 00:06:22.430
We are talking about
the modern day slavery.

00:06:22.430 --> 00:06:23.930
ERIC SCHMIDT: I
think maybe everyone

00:06:23.930 --> 00:06:25.096
is having the same reaction.

00:06:25.096 --> 00:06:28.369
How is this possible today?

00:06:28.369 --> 00:06:29.910
KAILASH SATYARTHI:
It is the reality.

00:06:29.910 --> 00:06:41.760
And I would say that
the saddest commentary

00:06:41.760 --> 00:06:47.890
on modern times in one sentence
is that child slavery still

00:06:47.890 --> 00:06:49.260
exists.

00:06:49.260 --> 00:06:53.870
And this is possible because
we don't have enough political

00:06:53.870 --> 00:06:58.430
will to control the systems.

00:06:58.430 --> 00:07:00.700
It is also because
of the social mindset

00:07:00.700 --> 00:07:04.750
which does not
recognize and respect

00:07:04.750 --> 00:07:07.230
the dignity of
childhood and dignity

00:07:07.230 --> 00:07:13.110
of children, so social customs
and so on, cultural problems.

00:07:13.110 --> 00:07:21.940
Also, we have not been
able invested adequate

00:07:21.940 --> 00:07:24.070
for our children.

00:07:24.070 --> 00:07:29.690
Look, only $18 billion
additional funding

00:07:29.690 --> 00:07:34.920
is needed annually to bring all
children to school and educate.

00:07:34.920 --> 00:07:40.220
And that is less than a
week's military expenditure

00:07:40.220 --> 00:07:43.050
of the world.

00:07:43.050 --> 00:07:44.050
We are not so poor.

00:07:44.050 --> 00:07:46.920
But even then, we are
not able to invest

00:07:46.920 --> 00:07:51.870
enough on our children, on their
health, on their protection.

00:07:51.870 --> 00:07:54.120
We don't have
protective systems.

00:07:54.120 --> 00:07:55.140
That is also problem.

00:07:55.140 --> 00:07:58.205
So this combination of these
things keep on working.

00:07:58.205 --> 00:08:00.080
ERIC SCHMIDT: But there's
a whole convention.

00:08:00.080 --> 00:08:01.277
There's a set of laws.

00:08:01.277 --> 00:08:03.360
There's something called
the Internationally Labor

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:05.100
Organization, and rules.

00:08:05.100 --> 00:08:07.610
America, for example, with
exception of agriculture

00:08:07.610 --> 00:08:11.260
has rules where you can't
be employed below 12.

00:08:11.260 --> 00:08:13.950
At 14, you can, but with
certain restrictions.

00:08:13.950 --> 00:08:17.480
At 16, you can, but with some
restrictions around danger.

00:08:17.480 --> 00:08:19.570
And at 18, you're
considered an adult.

00:08:19.570 --> 00:08:22.210
And I think that conforms
roughly with the rules.

00:08:22.210 --> 00:08:24.000
Is the problem that
they signed the law,

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:25.375
and then they
don't implement it?

00:08:25.375 --> 00:08:28.074
Or did they just
not sign the law?

00:08:28.074 --> 00:08:29.990
KAILASH SATYARTHI: Most
of them sign the laws.

00:08:29.990 --> 00:08:35.390
170 countries globally have
ratified the Convention

00:08:35.390 --> 00:08:36.780
on Worst Forms of Child Labor.

00:08:36.780 --> 00:08:38.299
That means no child
shall be allowed

00:08:38.299 --> 00:08:40.710
to work in hazardous
occupations in worst forms

00:08:40.710 --> 00:08:42.460
up to the age of 18.

00:08:42.460 --> 00:08:44.450
But despite that, it goes on.

00:08:44.450 --> 00:08:46.790
As I said, 85 million
children are the victims

00:08:46.790 --> 00:08:48.800
of worst forms of child labor.

00:08:48.800 --> 00:08:55.330
So one thing is moral
and legal accountability.

00:08:55.330 --> 00:08:58.780
Another thing is the serious
amount of political will

00:08:58.780 --> 00:09:00.450
which is lacking.

00:09:00.450 --> 00:09:02.490
And thirdly, strong
civil society,

00:09:02.490 --> 00:09:04.235
because the politicians
act when there

00:09:04.235 --> 00:09:07.240
is a demand from their voters
or from the communities

00:09:07.240 --> 00:09:08.620
and societies.

00:09:08.620 --> 00:09:10.480
And these children whom
we are talking about

00:09:10.480 --> 00:09:12.100
are neither the
voters, or nor they

00:09:12.100 --> 00:09:14.750
can influence the
politics of any country.

00:09:14.750 --> 00:09:19.900
So that's why it is very, very
important than the voices,

00:09:19.900 --> 00:09:23.030
strong voices should come
in favor of children,

00:09:23.030 --> 00:09:25.700
because children are not
able to speak for themselves.

00:09:25.700 --> 00:09:32.780
They are almost invisible,
most ignored and neglected.

00:09:32.780 --> 00:09:37.230
Civil society is not so
cohesive and strong that

00:09:37.230 --> 00:09:39.390
can speak with
one voice and hold

00:09:39.390 --> 00:09:41.100
the government accountable.

00:09:41.100 --> 00:09:42.630
Also, the business
is accountable,

00:09:42.630 --> 00:09:45.000
because businesses also
have very strong role

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.060
to play, especially when it
comes to the supply chain.

00:09:48.060 --> 00:09:50.820
Most of the products are
now which we are using,

00:09:50.820 --> 00:09:52.970
from [INAUDIBLE] to shoes,
and many more things,

00:09:52.970 --> 00:09:55.670
are produced by children in
different parts of the world,

00:09:55.670 --> 00:09:58.950
by the suppliers and the
local subcontractors,

00:09:58.950 --> 00:10:00.360
petty contractors.

00:10:00.360 --> 00:10:03.220
So more transparency,
more accountability

00:10:03.220 --> 00:10:06.590
in the entire supply chain
and the global business

00:10:06.590 --> 00:10:07.820
is equally needed.

00:10:07.820 --> 00:10:10.680
So the combination of
those things are missing.

00:10:10.680 --> 00:10:13.340
ERIC SCHMIDT: You know, you
created this Save the Children

00:10:13.340 --> 00:10:16.670
movement, and you're credited
with saving somewhere

00:10:16.670 --> 00:10:19.310
between 60,000 and
100,000 children

00:10:19.310 --> 00:10:23.800
from this sort of thing in
India and with many hundreds

00:10:23.800 --> 00:10:25.260
of villages that you worked.

00:10:25.260 --> 00:10:28.970
What did you actually
do to make this happen?

00:10:28.970 --> 00:10:30.030
Was it speaking?

00:10:30.030 --> 00:10:32.890
Was it visiting?

00:10:32.890 --> 00:10:35.400
How did you do it?

00:10:35.400 --> 00:10:38.430
KAILASH SATYARTHI:
Well, every day

00:10:38.430 --> 00:10:43.430
when I come to my office
in South Delhi, in Kalkaji,

00:10:43.430 --> 00:10:49.470
almost every day, I find one,
at least, but sometimes more,

00:10:49.470 --> 00:10:54.420
parents are sitting and waiting
for my people and me to help.

00:10:54.420 --> 00:10:56.120
Whose children are missing?

00:10:56.120 --> 00:10:58.730
Whose children are
trafficked and sold?

00:10:58.730 --> 00:11:01.370
They could not raise
those children.

00:11:01.370 --> 00:11:03.730
And they have no hope,
because they cannot easily go

00:11:03.730 --> 00:11:04.490
to the police.

00:11:04.490 --> 00:11:07.610
The poor people in most of
the developing countries

00:11:07.610 --> 00:11:09.480
don't have faith in
police, number one,

00:11:09.480 --> 00:11:12.120
and no confidence in police.

00:11:12.120 --> 00:11:12.980
Anyway.

00:11:12.980 --> 00:11:14.040
So they keep on waiting.

00:11:14.040 --> 00:11:16.500
So what we do, on
the basis of that,

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:21.280
we do thorough investigation
about the clues they give

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:23.230
and the knowledge they give.

00:11:23.230 --> 00:11:26.860
Then we engage different
authorities-- police,

00:11:26.860 --> 00:11:29.650
magistrate, the
legal department.

00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:32.780
It is not so easy to coordinate
with different agencies,

00:11:32.780 --> 00:11:34.400
but we had to.

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:38.470
And then be conducted
secret rescue operations.

00:11:38.470 --> 00:11:41.250
In that operation, we
don't inform anyone,

00:11:41.250 --> 00:11:43.440
even don't inform the
police the exact location.

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:45.770
We say that in that
area, these children

00:11:45.770 --> 00:11:48.850
are confined in the
factory or a mine,

00:11:48.850 --> 00:11:50.104
because it's always risky.

00:11:50.104 --> 00:11:51.270
I lost two of my colleagues.

00:11:51.270 --> 00:11:52.020
One was shot dead.

00:11:52.020 --> 00:11:53.106
One was beaten to death.

00:11:53.106 --> 00:11:53.980
ERIC SCHMIDT: Really?

00:11:53.980 --> 00:11:54.979
KAILASH SATYARTHI: Yeah.

00:11:54.979 --> 00:11:59.860
And I had my left foot
broken, my leg broken.

00:11:59.860 --> 00:12:02.730
My right shoulder is broken.

00:12:02.730 --> 00:12:05.250
My backbone has a lot
of bruises and scars.

00:12:05.250 --> 00:12:07.220
My head has scars.

00:12:07.220 --> 00:12:10.000
So these people are very
strong people, mafia.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.900
And if they come to know in
advance that we are going

00:12:12.900 --> 00:12:17.200
to rescue children, then
they're prepared with arms

00:12:17.200 --> 00:12:19.290
and become violent.

00:12:19.290 --> 00:12:21.580
So we have to be very,
very, very careful too,

00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:28.159
and very swift and secret to go
and do the rescue operations.

00:12:28.159 --> 00:12:30.200
ERIC SCHMIDT: I'm, sorry,
so you literally go in?

00:12:30.200 --> 00:12:30.890
KAILASH SATYARTHI:
Very literally.

00:12:30.890 --> 00:12:31.260
ERIC SCHMIDT: And
rescue the child.

00:12:31.260 --> 00:12:32.350
KAILASH SATYARTHI: Yeah,
thousands of times.

00:12:32.350 --> 00:12:34.180
I have gone personally
thousands of times.

00:12:34.180 --> 00:12:37.190
I could not recall how many
times in the last 35 years.

00:12:37.190 --> 00:12:41.090
But right from the beginning,
I go, and my colleague go.

00:12:41.090 --> 00:12:43.800
And earlier, the police
was not so involved.

00:12:43.800 --> 00:12:48.210
But later on, when the high
courts and the Supreme Court

00:12:48.210 --> 00:12:52.140
of India became quite
proactive and started

00:12:52.140 --> 00:12:53.890
directing the
authorities and police

00:12:53.890 --> 00:12:57.230
to help and to go in these
rescue operations, only

00:12:57.230 --> 00:12:58.820
then they started going.

00:12:58.820 --> 00:13:01.520
So when we free
the children back,

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:05.300
there are a lot of legal
formalities in terms of handing

00:13:05.300 --> 00:13:08.620
them over to the parents.

00:13:08.620 --> 00:13:12.520
And then we bring those children
for rehabilitation centers.

00:13:12.520 --> 00:13:16.030
My organization runs three
rehabilitation centers,

00:13:16.030 --> 00:13:18.750
one for girls and two for boys.

00:13:18.750 --> 00:13:21.160
And these children stay there.

00:13:21.160 --> 00:13:28.250
And we try to restore their
childhood and sense of freedom.

00:13:28.250 --> 00:13:30.820
But more importantly, we
build their self-esteem

00:13:30.820 --> 00:13:32.790
so some of them can
become the leaders

00:13:32.790 --> 00:13:35.660
and liberators for themselves.

00:13:35.660 --> 00:13:41.200
Some of my children came to
address the UN General Assembly

00:13:41.200 --> 00:13:42.520
side meetings.

00:13:42.520 --> 00:13:46.420
Some of them have
addressed the Senate

00:13:46.420 --> 00:13:48.580
and congressional
hearings in DC.

00:13:48.580 --> 00:13:52.480
Some of them have addressed
the European Parliament.

00:13:52.480 --> 00:13:54.480
So they have proven
that if they are

00:13:54.480 --> 00:13:56.950
given the chance
and opportunities,

00:13:56.950 --> 00:13:59.787
they are no less than
anyone in the world.

00:13:59.787 --> 00:14:01.620
And they have shown
their leadership skills.

00:14:01.620 --> 00:14:03.453
ERIC SCHMIDT: And what
happens to the people

00:14:03.453 --> 00:14:06.470
who would enslave them?

00:14:06.470 --> 00:14:09.360
KAILASH SATYARTHI: We have
strict laws on slavery

00:14:09.360 --> 00:14:11.580
and human trafficking.

00:14:11.580 --> 00:14:16.510
So sometimes the problem is that
the civil society organizations

00:14:16.510 --> 00:14:19.360
have no idea, and
sometimes they don't

00:14:19.360 --> 00:14:22.900
have capacity to use the
laws, because, first off all,

00:14:22.900 --> 00:14:24.100
it is very risky.

00:14:24.100 --> 00:14:27.710
If you will use against
those mafias, legally.

00:14:27.710 --> 00:14:32.190
The softer approach is just to
take the help of authorities

00:14:32.190 --> 00:14:35.030
and go and convince and take
the children out and send them

00:14:35.030 --> 00:14:36.180
back home.

00:14:36.180 --> 00:14:37.000
That is not enough.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.270
But in my case, our
organization has

00:14:39.270 --> 00:14:41.220
been working for the
enactment of laws,

00:14:41.220 --> 00:14:44.540
for the enforcement of
laws, because if we rescue

00:14:44.540 --> 00:14:47.100
these children under
the proper laws,

00:14:47.100 --> 00:14:49.270
they would be entitled
for the rehabilitation

00:14:49.270 --> 00:14:51.150
facilities and the governments.

00:14:51.150 --> 00:14:54.000
And their employers
would be arrested.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.210
Of course, in many cases,
employers run away.

00:14:56.210 --> 00:14:59.610
We cannot find them when we
go for rescue operations.

00:14:59.610 --> 00:15:03.930
But sometimes they are
caught, sooner or later.

00:15:03.930 --> 00:15:05.960
And then they are arrested.

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:08.210
Of course, it's a very
cumbersome, very expensive

00:15:08.210 --> 00:15:13.130
process to follow the
legal case in the court.

00:15:13.130 --> 00:15:15.330
And they are rich
and powerful people.

00:15:15.330 --> 00:15:18.060
They can go to higher court,
and then higher court.

00:15:18.060 --> 00:15:22.275
So it's difficult, but at least
there is some deterrent in it.

00:15:22.275 --> 00:15:25.570
ERIC SCHMIDT: Now, is every one
of these children illiterate,

00:15:25.570 --> 00:15:26.070
essentially?

00:15:26.070 --> 00:15:27.634
They've not been to school?

00:15:27.634 --> 00:15:29.800
KAILASH SATYARTHI: Some of
them have been to school.

00:15:29.800 --> 00:15:33.560
Many of them have
never been to school.

00:15:33.560 --> 00:15:35.430
Some of them are
registered in the schools,

00:15:35.430 --> 00:15:36.960
but they don't
attend the school.

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:40.190
For instance, last year, we
have rescued 1,100 children

00:15:40.190 --> 00:15:42.110
from Delhi itself, from
the capital of India,

00:15:42.110 --> 00:15:44.720
with the help of
judiciary and police

00:15:44.720 --> 00:15:46.590
in these rescue operations.

00:15:46.590 --> 00:15:52.600
And 850 out of
them were enrolled

00:15:52.600 --> 00:15:55.180
in their native villages
in their schools.

00:15:55.180 --> 00:15:57.770
That means they were attending.

00:15:57.770 --> 00:16:00.740
All the datas
which were prepared

00:16:00.740 --> 00:16:02.670
was that these children
were in schools.

00:16:02.670 --> 00:16:05.030
They were receiving a
stipend, and other facilities

00:16:05.030 --> 00:16:06.900
of the government.

00:16:06.900 --> 00:16:10.830
And the local government
furnishes that information

00:16:10.830 --> 00:16:12.690
to Indian Parliament.

00:16:12.690 --> 00:16:15.370
And the Indian government
furnishes that information

00:16:15.370 --> 00:16:18.340
to UNESCO and other UN agencies.

00:16:18.340 --> 00:16:21.040
So they were attending
those things on paper,

00:16:21.040 --> 00:16:23.770
but they were enslaved,
and they were trafficked.

00:16:23.770 --> 00:16:27.720
So many of these children
are removed from schools

00:16:27.720 --> 00:16:31.670
with the protection of better
life and better living,

00:16:31.670 --> 00:16:34.690
working conditions and so on.

00:16:34.690 --> 00:16:38.587
And these traffickers
are quite smart people.

00:16:38.587 --> 00:16:39.295
They move around.

00:16:39.295 --> 00:16:41.410
They identify certain areas.

00:16:41.410 --> 00:16:44.880
They engage the local
agents, subagents,

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:47.250
and they successfully
bring the children

00:16:47.250 --> 00:16:50.880
and sell them out
to different places,

00:16:50.880 --> 00:16:55.346
including for child marriages,
or brothels, or other places.

00:16:55.346 --> 00:16:56.970
ERIC SCHMIDT: The
obvious question here

00:16:56.970 --> 00:17:01.740
is, how much of this is sexual
exploitation of young men

00:17:01.740 --> 00:17:03.130
and women, boys and girls?

00:17:03.130 --> 00:17:07.782
And how much of it is
other forms of abuse?

00:17:07.782 --> 00:17:09.240
KAILASH SATYARTHI:
The sexual abuse

00:17:09.240 --> 00:17:12.250
goes beyond the child labor or
child slavery or trafficking

00:17:12.250 --> 00:17:16.859
issue, because sexual abuse
may occur inside the families

00:17:16.859 --> 00:17:19.849
by some of the distant
relatives or in neighborhood,

00:17:19.849 --> 00:17:21.829
in schools also sometimes.

00:17:21.829 --> 00:17:24.010
It is not very uncommon
in many of the developing

00:17:24.010 --> 00:17:28.960
countries, the sexual
abuse in different forms.

00:17:28.960 --> 00:17:37.210
But when it comes to the
slavery and child labor,

00:17:37.210 --> 00:17:42.420
commercial sexual exploitation
or child prostitution

00:17:42.420 --> 00:17:44.030
is a very, very heinous crime.

00:17:44.030 --> 00:17:45.950
What else could be
worse than that,

00:17:45.950 --> 00:17:48.320
sexual slavery for children?

00:17:48.320 --> 00:17:53.510
But when we compare with the
rest of the exploitative forms

00:17:53.510 --> 00:17:58.970
of child labor and child
slavery, it's a small segment.

00:17:58.970 --> 00:18:01.690
I'm talking about
168 million children

00:18:01.690 --> 00:18:08.060
in full time jobs, where
a few million children are

00:18:08.060 --> 00:18:13.980
the victims of child sexual
exploitation as child slaves.

00:18:13.980 --> 00:18:19.590
But the newer forms are
evolving, like the pornography.

00:18:19.590 --> 00:18:22.670
The children are being used
for the pornographic proposes,

00:18:22.670 --> 00:18:24.520
knowingly or unknowingly.

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:28.110
They have no awareness
how they would be

00:18:28.110 --> 00:18:30.750
used by the small smartphone.

00:18:30.750 --> 00:18:32.560
People who were
carrying a smartphone,

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:36.290
they take the pictures,
they change the photo,

00:18:36.290 --> 00:18:39.920
and then blackmail
the young girls.

00:18:39.920 --> 00:18:45.640
And that has become quite common
using this modern technology.

00:18:45.640 --> 00:18:49.630
So the awareness among
the youth and children

00:18:49.630 --> 00:18:52.450
in schools and
colleges is very less,

00:18:52.450 --> 00:18:57.870
that how to get rid of these
blackmailers and the people who

00:18:57.870 --> 00:19:01.870
can manipulate their
pictures and so on.

00:19:01.870 --> 00:19:06.020
Also, the tracking about such
people is equally important

00:19:06.020 --> 00:19:10.120
and how to address this problem
with the service providers,

00:19:10.120 --> 00:19:13.660
for instance, both in case
of the phone companies

00:19:13.660 --> 00:19:20.890
as well as the websites
and other social media.

00:19:20.890 --> 00:19:24.070
These things are new
challenges in the exploitation

00:19:24.070 --> 00:19:25.730
of children in modern times.

00:19:25.730 --> 00:19:28.350
ERIC SCHMIDT: It's
important to address it.

00:19:28.350 --> 00:19:32.130
You're here in New York to visit
with United Nations, I believe.

00:19:37.690 --> 00:19:40.410
Tell us, how do you
actually do this at scale?

00:19:40.410 --> 00:19:43.840
I understand you go in
and you rescue a child,

00:19:43.840 --> 00:19:45.550
very dangerous, and so forth.

00:19:45.550 --> 00:19:50.170
But with 168 million children
in this kind of situation,

00:19:50.170 --> 00:19:52.572
you need a scalable approach.

00:19:52.572 --> 00:19:54.480
What's the best
way to start this?

00:19:54.480 --> 00:19:56.440
You're talking to the UN
now about this, right?

00:19:56.440 --> 00:19:57.530
KAILASH SATYARTHI: Yeah.

00:19:57.530 --> 00:20:01.070
I have been to UN several
times, not the first time.

00:20:01.070 --> 00:20:02.850
I realized right
from the beginning

00:20:02.850 --> 00:20:09.620
that rescuing 1 or 10 or
100 children is not enough.

00:20:09.620 --> 00:20:14.330
When I started in
1981, after giving up

00:20:14.330 --> 00:20:18.210
my career as an electrical
engineer, it was very hard.

00:20:18.210 --> 00:20:19.800
Many of you must
have been genius.

00:20:19.800 --> 00:20:22.950
In those days, we did not
have the software engineering

00:20:22.950 --> 00:20:26.530
or the computer sciences, so
I did not go to that course.

00:20:26.530 --> 00:20:29.580
So the most advanced was
electrical engineering.

00:20:29.580 --> 00:20:32.690
And one has to secure
very, very good marks

00:20:32.690 --> 00:20:35.940
to get admission in electric
engineering in those days,

00:20:35.940 --> 00:20:36.720
40 years ago.

00:20:39.470 --> 00:20:45.350
Anyway, so those days, we did
not have any law in India.

00:20:45.350 --> 00:20:47.500
The United Nations
systems did not

00:20:47.500 --> 00:20:51.510
have any international
convention

00:20:51.510 --> 00:20:53.460
on rights of children.

00:20:53.460 --> 00:20:55.830
It came into being
only in 1989 when

00:20:55.830 --> 00:20:57.720
UN Convention on the
Rights of the Children

00:20:57.720 --> 00:21:00.410
was adopted by the
international community.

00:21:00.410 --> 00:21:01.660
So it was a hard time.

00:21:01.660 --> 00:21:05.610
But we realized, I realized
that we have to fight for laws.

00:21:05.610 --> 00:21:07.140
Without that, we cannot.

00:21:07.140 --> 00:21:10.550
So we fought for it in 1985.

00:21:10.550 --> 00:21:12.210
We succeeded in '86.

00:21:12.210 --> 00:21:14.300
There was a new law in
India, the first time,

00:21:14.300 --> 00:21:17.580
the Indian law against child
labor has been enacted.

00:21:17.580 --> 00:21:18.650
We knew it.

00:21:18.650 --> 00:21:22.155
Then be tried to link this
whole issue with education.

00:21:22.155 --> 00:21:24.850
Right from the beginning,
I was advocating

00:21:24.850 --> 00:21:29.610
that eradication of child labor
and education for children

00:21:29.610 --> 00:21:31.660
are the two sides of same coin.

00:21:31.660 --> 00:21:35.010
We have to ensure that the
government have good policies,

00:21:35.010 --> 00:21:38.050
good programs, good investment
on education for children,

00:21:38.050 --> 00:21:41.330
has preventive measures as well
as rehabilitative measures.

00:21:41.330 --> 00:21:44.630
Then we realized that it
is not an Indian problem

00:21:44.630 --> 00:21:46.620
because many of the
multinational companies

00:21:46.620 --> 00:21:48.270
are operating in India.

00:21:48.270 --> 00:21:49.840
All of the products
made in India

00:21:49.840 --> 00:21:52.120
are sold in other
parts of the world.

00:21:52.120 --> 00:21:56.190
The global political policies
and economic policies

00:21:56.190 --> 00:21:59.810
are also affecting children in
different parts of the world.

00:21:59.810 --> 00:22:04.850
So I had an idea to launch
a worldwide movement

00:22:04.850 --> 00:22:08.690
against child labor
with a clear demand

00:22:08.690 --> 00:22:11.520
that international
communities should

00:22:11.520 --> 00:22:16.100
adopt a new international law
on worst forms of child labor.

00:22:16.100 --> 00:22:20.990
In 1989, we organized
a worldwide march,

00:22:20.990 --> 00:22:22.550
a global march
against child labor,

00:22:22.550 --> 00:22:24.450
which went across 103 countries.

00:22:24.450 --> 00:22:28.530
We have covered 80,000 kilometer
distance, which is double

00:22:28.530 --> 00:22:30.500
the periphery of the earth.

00:22:30.500 --> 00:22:35.240
And 71 heads of the nations--
presidents, prime ministers,

00:22:35.240 --> 00:22:37.970
kings, and queens--
joined or supported it.

00:22:37.970 --> 00:22:40.420
It had resulted in the
international legislation which

00:22:40.420 --> 00:22:43.750
we are talking about now, this
worst forms of child labor law.

00:22:43.750 --> 00:22:47.610
Similarly, we
realized, I realized

00:22:47.610 --> 00:22:51.180
that I'm freeing 10 children,
but another 20 or 30 children

00:22:51.180 --> 00:22:54.300
are entering into
slavery, trafficked,

00:22:54.300 --> 00:22:56.606
to work in carpet
industry in India.

00:22:56.606 --> 00:23:03.960
And I trusted in the
power of human compassion.

00:23:03.960 --> 00:23:07.220
And everybody has some
element of humanity.

00:23:07.220 --> 00:23:09.200
That was my belief.

00:23:09.200 --> 00:23:14.270
90% of the carpets produced
in India, and 95%, those days,

00:23:14.270 --> 00:23:16.310
produced in Pakistan
and Nepal, they

00:23:16.310 --> 00:23:18.530
were sold to United
States and Germany

00:23:18.530 --> 00:23:20.790
and other European countries.

00:23:20.790 --> 00:23:23.750
So an idea cropped up
in my mind that why

00:23:23.750 --> 00:23:27.440
should I not go to the consumers
and launch the campaign

00:23:27.440 --> 00:23:32.930
to educate them, not to call for
boycott of South Asian carpets,

00:23:32.930 --> 00:23:35.250
but with an alternate,
with a solution,

00:23:35.250 --> 00:23:37.100
because I always
believe in solutions.

00:23:37.100 --> 00:23:40.270
Problems, one can talk hours
and hours and days and months.

00:23:40.270 --> 00:23:43.370
It's very easy to talk
about the problems,

00:23:43.370 --> 00:23:45.680
but sometimes difficult.

00:23:45.680 --> 00:23:48.730
But solution is must.

00:23:48.730 --> 00:23:54.630
So I brought an idea that let
evolve a social monitoring

00:23:54.630 --> 00:23:59.610
and labeling mechanism
through proper inspection,

00:23:59.610 --> 00:24:02.860
transparent and professional
inspection mechanism,

00:24:02.860 --> 00:24:05.600
running numbers of the carpet,
the code numbers and so

00:24:05.600 --> 00:24:08.980
on, which can guarantee
that this particular rug is

00:24:08.980 --> 00:24:11.800
free of child labor
in South Asia.

00:24:11.800 --> 00:24:14.660
So that was the
first social labeling

00:24:14.660 --> 00:24:20.840
introduced when the [INAUDIBLE]
corporate social responsibility

00:24:20.840 --> 00:24:21.880
was not coined.

00:24:21.880 --> 00:24:22.830
It was not invented.

00:24:22.830 --> 00:24:26.190
Before CSR, we had
a successful story

00:24:26.190 --> 00:24:28.590
to tell about the
carpet industry.

00:24:28.590 --> 00:24:31.240
And the number of
child laborers,

00:24:31.240 --> 00:24:34.890
according to various studies,
including the US Department

00:24:34.890 --> 00:24:40.060
of Labor, those days in
mid '90s, was 1 million

00:24:40.060 --> 00:24:42.120
in India, Pakistan, and Nepal.

00:24:42.120 --> 00:24:45.070
And the latest figures
suggest that it

00:24:45.070 --> 00:24:48.900
is no more than 200,000.

00:24:48.900 --> 00:24:52.270
So there was a
significant decrease

00:24:52.270 --> 00:24:55.970
in the number of child
laborers in carpet industry.

00:24:55.970 --> 00:25:00.870
And as a result, we can
find job opportunities

00:25:00.870 --> 00:25:04.730
to 800,000 adult people
in place of children,

00:25:04.730 --> 00:25:07.150
because the quantity of
carpet did not fall down.

00:25:07.150 --> 00:25:08.310
It is even more.

00:25:08.310 --> 00:25:12.840
So many more adults could
find job in place of children.

00:25:12.840 --> 00:25:15.110
So that was one thing.

00:25:15.110 --> 00:25:19.950
ERIC SCHMIDT: So when you talk,
it sounds like this problem--

00:25:19.950 --> 00:25:21.940
and you've done
your work in India--

00:25:21.940 --> 00:25:24.300
but it must be a
pretty global problem.

00:25:24.300 --> 00:25:25.740
So it's a problem in India.

00:25:25.740 --> 00:25:27.722
It's a problem in Southern Asia.

00:25:27.722 --> 00:25:28.930
That's a problem in Pakistan.

00:25:28.930 --> 00:25:30.832
Where else is it a problem?

00:25:30.832 --> 00:25:32.540
KAILASH SATYARTHI:
It's a global problem.

00:25:32.540 --> 00:25:36.310
As you mentioned, that there's
a problem in United States

00:25:36.310 --> 00:25:37.640
as well.

00:25:37.640 --> 00:25:41.710
In the West Coast, we have
children, Hispanic children

00:25:41.710 --> 00:25:44.460
still working in agriculture,
farms, and other places,

00:25:44.460 --> 00:25:46.015
and sweatshops also
in some places.

00:25:50.420 --> 00:25:51.710
I started in India.

00:25:51.710 --> 00:25:53.725
Then I realized that it
is a South Asian issue,

00:25:53.725 --> 00:25:55.760
so I started working
in Pakistan, Nepal,

00:25:55.760 --> 00:25:57.180
and Bangladesh.

00:25:57.180 --> 00:26:01.120
And then, after the
global march in 1998,

00:26:01.120 --> 00:26:04.530
we built a worldwide platform,
or worldwide coalition

00:26:04.530 --> 00:26:10.480
of civil society organizations,
teachers unions, trade unions,

00:26:10.480 --> 00:26:13.750
some of the businesses,
and brought them

00:26:13.750 --> 00:26:16.500
in one platform, that is Global
March Against Child Labor.

00:26:16.500 --> 00:26:18.400
We kept the name intact.

00:26:18.400 --> 00:26:21.980
So we work in more than 100
countries, practically, now.

00:26:21.980 --> 00:26:24.430
We have our regional
offices and coordinators

00:26:24.430 --> 00:26:29.760
in South Africa, Central
Africa, East Africa,

00:26:29.760 --> 00:26:33.310
similarly southern
part of America,

00:26:33.310 --> 00:26:35.450
and Central America,
and North America,

00:26:35.450 --> 00:26:40.510
similarly in Asia, South Asia,
and Southeast Asia, Europe.

00:26:40.510 --> 00:26:46.100
So we work through 2,000
partners across 144 countries,

00:26:46.100 --> 00:26:47.390
to be precise.

00:26:47.390 --> 00:26:49.910
But some of them are
dormant and not so active.

00:26:49.910 --> 00:26:51.570
But about 100
countries are active,

00:26:51.570 --> 00:26:54.380
where we can raise
the collective voice.

00:26:54.380 --> 00:26:56.220
ERIC SCHMIDT: So I
think what we should

00:26:56.220 --> 00:26:58.920
do is we should go to the
questions from the audience.

00:26:58.920 --> 00:27:01.346
And we also have
an internal system

00:27:01.346 --> 00:27:02.970
which we called Dory,
which has already

00:27:02.970 --> 00:27:04.867
submitted a few questions.

00:27:04.867 --> 00:27:06.700
So I'll ask the first
question, and maybe we

00:27:06.700 --> 00:27:08.824
can have people who have
comments or questions come

00:27:08.824 --> 00:27:10.280
to the microphones.

00:27:10.280 --> 00:27:13.540
First question on the Dory
is, "In India, we often

00:27:13.540 --> 00:27:15.660
see children from poor
backgrounds working

00:27:15.660 --> 00:27:18.490
in roadside shops,
factories, and mines.

00:27:18.490 --> 00:27:20.540
They and their parents
often support this,

00:27:20.540 --> 00:27:22.800
saying that if their
children don't work,

00:27:22.800 --> 00:27:25.300
they won't have enough
money to eat food.

00:27:25.300 --> 00:27:27.565
What is your answer
to this argument?"

00:27:27.565 --> 00:27:28.940
KAILASH SATYARTHI:
First off all,

00:27:28.940 --> 00:27:31.040
the children who are
working in the street,

00:27:31.040 --> 00:27:35.640
restaurants, or whatever,
mines, they are not

00:27:35.640 --> 00:27:37.970
responsible for poverty.

00:27:37.970 --> 00:27:39.220
Somebody else is responsible.

00:27:39.220 --> 00:27:41.840
This is the moral issue.

00:27:41.840 --> 00:27:44.240
Who will take the
responsibility of poverty?

00:27:44.240 --> 00:27:46.140
Why children should
take the responsibility

00:27:46.140 --> 00:27:48.751
on their shoulders,
to carry it on?

00:27:48.751 --> 00:27:50.750
And they will remain poor
for all of their life.

00:27:50.750 --> 00:27:52.070
They will remain illiterate.

00:27:52.070 --> 00:27:55.720
They will remain sick
while working as child.

00:27:55.720 --> 00:27:56.900
This is moral.

00:27:56.900 --> 00:28:01.960
But the economic argument
is that, globally, we

00:28:01.960 --> 00:28:06.180
have 168 million children,
as I said, in full time jobs,

00:28:06.180 --> 00:28:09.710
and 200 million
adults are jobless.

00:28:09.710 --> 00:28:12.690
There are many studies
in several countries

00:28:12.690 --> 00:28:17.150
which have proven that
there is a parallel

00:28:17.150 --> 00:28:20.950
between adult unemployment
and child labor.

00:28:20.950 --> 00:28:24.680
And also, most of these
children who are looking

00:28:24.680 --> 00:28:26.920
are the very children
of those parents

00:28:26.920 --> 00:28:30.750
who don't find jobs for
more than 100 days a year.

00:28:30.750 --> 00:28:33.351
So that becomes
a vicious circle.

00:28:33.351 --> 00:28:35.850
Children are preferred in jobs
because they are the cheapest

00:28:35.850 --> 00:28:37.650
