to deal with the forced labor,
child labor, and bonded labor.

00:41:58.350 --> 00:42:04.900
And the Department of Labor
produces a frequent report.

00:42:04.900 --> 00:42:07.570
It's, I think, four yearly
or three yearly report which

00:42:07.570 --> 00:42:10.110
is brought, and they
name the industries

00:42:10.110 --> 00:42:12.730
in countries which
involve child labor

00:42:12.730 --> 00:42:16.480
and try to negotiate
and pressurize

00:42:16.480 --> 00:42:19.820
the countries of import,
as well as the industries.

00:42:19.820 --> 00:42:23.970
But the blanket ban on any
industrial or any country

00:42:23.970 --> 00:42:27.140
is not going to
solve the problem.

00:42:27.140 --> 00:42:30.210
There are other ways
to deal with it,

00:42:30.210 --> 00:42:33.730
as I've mentioned before, that
how to engage the suppliers

00:42:33.730 --> 00:42:37.660
and supply chain, how to create
more protective environment

00:42:37.660 --> 00:42:42.080
for children, how to invest
more on education for children

00:42:42.080 --> 00:42:46.650
in those communities,
how to raise

00:42:46.650 --> 00:42:50.280
the consciousness in
the communities itself,

00:42:50.280 --> 00:42:52.250
because communities
and parents themselves

00:42:52.250 --> 00:42:55.040
could be the very best
protector of those children.

00:42:55.040 --> 00:42:59.280
They can be involved in it,
which is normally not done.

00:42:59.280 --> 00:43:02.370
So awareness building and
consciousness raising,

00:43:02.370 --> 00:43:07.700
engagement of the suppliers
and the subcontractors,

00:43:07.700 --> 00:43:11.530
building their capacity,
sensitizing them is important.

00:43:11.530 --> 00:43:16.860
Equally important to form the
multi-stakeholders initiative,

00:43:16.860 --> 00:43:20.550
where the governments,
if possible,

00:43:20.550 --> 00:43:22.830
but the businesses,
the civil society

00:43:22.830 --> 00:43:25.420
organizations,
community organizations,

00:43:25.420 --> 00:43:31.020
religious groups, the
teachers, the faith leaders

00:43:31.020 --> 00:43:34.145
can come together and help
in finding the solution.

00:43:34.145 --> 00:43:35.630
And of course, the
representatives

00:43:35.630 --> 00:43:38.920
of the subcontractors
and suppliers

00:43:38.920 --> 00:43:42.310
should also be brought into
account so that everybody

00:43:42.310 --> 00:43:44.200
can work hand in hand.

00:43:44.200 --> 00:43:46.250
So wherever we have
been able to find

00:43:46.250 --> 00:43:48.750
some sort of
multi-stakeholders initiative,

00:43:48.750 --> 00:43:50.410
we have seen some
positive results.

00:43:50.410 --> 00:43:52.560
But that has to trickle
down at local level.

00:43:52.560 --> 00:43:58.941
It should not remain an
international stakeholders

00:43:58.941 --> 00:43:59.440
initiative.

00:43:59.440 --> 00:44:02.820
It should go down at district
level, or state level, country

00:44:02.820 --> 00:44:03.530
level.

00:44:03.530 --> 00:44:06.940
And that process, this
is not just one go thing.

00:44:06.940 --> 00:44:09.340
It's an ongoing
process for education,

00:44:09.340 --> 00:44:11.570
and making the
people responsible

00:44:11.570 --> 00:44:13.123
and eventually accountable.

00:44:13.123 --> 00:44:13.956
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:44:13.956 --> 00:44:15.122
ERIC SCHMIDT: OK, thank you.

00:44:15.122 --> 00:44:16.084
Yes, go ahead.

00:44:16.084 --> 00:44:17.500
AUDIENCE: You spoke
briefly before

00:44:17.500 --> 00:44:19.867
about deterrents
that are in place.

00:44:19.867 --> 00:44:21.950
I was hoping you could
elaborate a little bit more

00:44:21.950 --> 00:44:24.250
about the deterrents in
place, where you think

00:44:24.250 --> 00:44:29.750
they might be falling short
on the social, economic, legal

00:44:29.750 --> 00:44:32.590
levels, and looking
at it not just

00:44:32.590 --> 00:44:36.124
from within Southeast
Asian countries, globally,

00:44:36.124 --> 00:44:38.290
but the local levels, like
you were just mentioning.

00:44:43.910 --> 00:44:46.700
KAILASH SATYARTHI: Actually,
the laws are important.

00:44:46.700 --> 00:44:51.350
But they are like the
tools, or the weapons.

00:44:51.350 --> 00:44:57.150
Somebody should use those tools
at the right time, right place.

00:44:57.150 --> 00:44:59.330
And that education
and that capacity

00:44:59.330 --> 00:45:02.690
is needed when we talk of law.

00:45:02.690 --> 00:45:07.400
Then the more important
is creating awareness

00:45:07.400 --> 00:45:14.120
in the society and holding
the stakeholders more morally

00:45:14.120 --> 00:45:16.140
accountable and
socially accountable.

00:45:16.140 --> 00:45:18.800
The accountability is
something which is missing.

00:45:18.800 --> 00:45:25.100
And accountability should be
evolved as a culture, not just

00:45:25.100 --> 00:45:27.230
as an imposition,
legal imposition

00:45:27.230 --> 00:45:29.390
that you have to show it.

00:45:29.390 --> 00:45:32.950
Combination of both would
be the best ideal situation,

00:45:32.950 --> 00:45:37.800
where the businesses and
other institutions, including

00:45:37.800 --> 00:45:41.730
the government should be held
accountable if they're not

00:45:41.730 --> 00:45:44.240
properly enforcing their laws.

00:45:44.240 --> 00:45:46.079
But on the other
hand, everybody should

00:45:46.079 --> 00:45:47.120
feel morally accountable.

00:45:47.120 --> 00:45:49.480
I think the moral
accountability is

00:45:49.480 --> 00:45:56.311
most effective and sustainable
than any other legal system.

00:45:56.311 --> 00:45:57.310
ERIC SCHMIDT: Thank you.

00:45:57.310 --> 00:45:58.740
Why don't we have our
last two questions

00:45:58.740 --> 00:45:59.800
right here on the left.

00:45:59.800 --> 00:46:00.450
Go ahead.

00:46:00.450 --> 00:46:01.720
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:46:01.720 --> 00:46:05.560
You mentioned that one of the
reasons that child labor is

00:46:05.560 --> 00:46:07.660
favored, obviously, is
that it's much cheaper.

00:46:07.660 --> 00:46:10.030
Children will work
for much longer days.

00:46:10.030 --> 00:46:12.580
Whereas an adult might only
work for eight hours a day,

00:46:12.580 --> 00:46:14.170
or something like that.

00:46:14.170 --> 00:46:17.330
So there's a clear
economic incentive.

00:46:17.330 --> 00:46:19.580
Do you think that
part of the problem

00:46:19.580 --> 00:46:22.170
might be over-regulation
of adult labor?

00:46:22.170 --> 00:46:24.740
That's clearly a very
tough position to take,

00:46:24.740 --> 00:46:26.990
but at the same time,
there must be some way

00:46:26.990 --> 00:46:30.000
that we can make the economic
incentive of choosing

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:33.100
child labor less favorable
for those companies.

00:46:33.100 --> 00:46:36.040
So do you think
it's in deregulation

00:46:36.040 --> 00:46:37.224
of other types of labor?

00:46:37.224 --> 00:46:38.640
Or do you think
there's other ways

00:46:38.640 --> 00:46:42.180
to close the gap of
making the incentive less?

00:46:44.970 --> 00:46:47.110
KAILASH SATYARTHI:
Actually, using child labor

00:46:47.110 --> 00:46:50.730
is illegal in most countries.

00:46:50.730 --> 00:46:56.100
So when they go for
employing child labor,

00:46:56.100 --> 00:46:59.560
they already do some
illegal activity.

00:46:59.560 --> 00:47:02.520
But by way of
employing children,

00:47:02.520 --> 00:47:05.040
they can save lot of
money as black money.

00:47:05.040 --> 00:47:08.580
On paper, most of these
people spent, 30%, 40%,

00:47:08.580 --> 00:47:12.180
50% of the production
cost as labor cost

00:47:12.180 --> 00:47:13.530
that is shown on paper.

00:47:13.530 --> 00:47:16.220
But practically, they
spend only 2%, 3%

00:47:16.220 --> 00:47:19.200
by feeding them or keeping them.

00:47:19.200 --> 00:47:21.320
Sometimes if they
give [INAUDIBLE],

00:47:21.320 --> 00:47:25.960
it would go up to 5%
of the total production

00:47:25.960 --> 00:47:28.020
cost, the labor component.

00:47:28.020 --> 00:47:32.300
But the rest of the money
goes as black money.

00:47:32.300 --> 00:47:37.580
And that black money propels
corruption and breaking

00:47:37.580 --> 00:47:38.380
the laws.

00:47:38.380 --> 00:47:41.000
So the people keep
on breaking the laws.

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:48.840
On the other hand,
the labor laws

00:47:48.840 --> 00:47:53.450
are not really so different
in most of the countries.

00:47:53.450 --> 00:47:57.540
In case of agriculture
labor, across the globe,

00:47:57.540 --> 00:48:00.200
but mainly in
developing countries,

00:48:00.200 --> 00:48:03.435
not properly implemented in
agriculture sector, no labor

00:48:03.435 --> 00:48:04.870
law, properly.

00:48:04.870 --> 00:48:11.730
Like, the minimum wage
and safety majors,

00:48:11.730 --> 00:48:12.755
they're not enforced.

00:48:15.580 --> 00:48:17.550
It is also a big,
big [INAUDIBLE]

00:48:17.550 --> 00:48:22.880
that how the very basic
labor laws in relation

00:48:22.880 --> 00:48:26.850
to minimum wage and
protection of workers

00:48:26.850 --> 00:48:31.190
is properly enforced,
which is not yet done.

00:48:31.190 --> 00:48:34.490
Only a few percent of people are
unionized, those who can fight.

00:48:34.490 --> 00:48:38.210
And they are clever to fight for
much better conditions, better

00:48:38.210 --> 00:48:39.730
wages, and so on.

00:48:39.730 --> 00:48:41.330
But the rest of the
people who are not

00:48:41.330 --> 00:48:49.700
unionized yet and living in
informal or unorganized sector,

00:48:49.700 --> 00:48:53.220
they are not even getting the
benefits of the existing laws.

00:48:53.220 --> 00:48:57.980
More important is to, first off
all, have good laws in relation

00:48:57.980 --> 00:49:03.100
to child labor and
effective implementation.

00:49:03.100 --> 00:49:05.220
And secondly,
investment on education

00:49:05.220 --> 00:49:08.350
is preventative measures.

00:49:08.350 --> 00:49:10.160
The answer lies in
education, basically.

00:49:13.090 --> 00:49:14.186
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:49:14.186 --> 00:49:17.050
ERIC SCHMIDT: Why don't
you have the last question.

00:49:17.050 --> 00:49:18.950
AUDIENCE: I was
just wondering, you

00:49:18.950 --> 00:49:22.350
mention about how you save all
these children from slavery,

00:49:22.350 --> 00:49:26.160
and also measures
on how to get buyers

00:49:26.160 --> 00:49:28.990
to stop buying the carpet
to prevent the income.

00:49:28.990 --> 00:49:30.960
But where do these children go?

00:49:30.960 --> 00:49:33.320
Because their families
are still in poverty.

00:49:33.320 --> 00:49:34.760
They still have to work.

00:49:34.760 --> 00:49:39.180
Is there any measures to make
sure they get educated instead?

00:49:39.180 --> 00:49:41.120
Where does the money from?

00:49:41.120 --> 00:49:43.230
KAILASH SATYARTHI: Yeah.

00:49:43.230 --> 00:49:46.380
There are many social
protection programs

00:49:46.380 --> 00:49:48.440
for children in many countries.

00:49:48.440 --> 00:49:52.220
For instance, in India, we
have very strong measures

00:49:52.220 --> 00:49:56.030
for rehabilitation of children
who are free from bonded labor.

00:49:56.030 --> 00:49:58.610
That is the part
of legal system.

00:49:58.610 --> 00:50:02.730
In Brazil, we have
very strong laws.

00:50:02.730 --> 00:50:06.130
In Philippines, there are
some strong schemes for that.

00:50:06.130 --> 00:50:07.960
There are many countries.

00:50:07.960 --> 00:50:11.080
So those schemes have
to be properly enforced.

00:50:11.080 --> 00:50:15.280
That is, again, a
challenge, also, because

00:50:15.280 --> 00:50:18.650
of weak coordination
among agencies,

00:50:18.650 --> 00:50:26.520
also because of
weak civil society,

00:50:26.520 --> 00:50:29.800
or incapable civil society to
raise their voice strongly.

00:50:29.800 --> 00:50:35.200
It goes on, no accountability.

00:50:35.200 --> 00:50:37.810
In case of carpet
you raised, I did not

00:50:37.810 --> 00:50:41.040
call for the total boycott
of South Asian carpets.

00:50:41.040 --> 00:50:44.810
I called for the child
labor free carpets.

00:50:44.810 --> 00:50:47.730
So the people should demand
child labor free carpet.

00:50:47.730 --> 00:50:51.190
Calling for boycott of
anything is an easy thing.

00:50:51.190 --> 00:50:53.510
But it did not work anywhere
in the world on any issue,

00:50:53.510 --> 00:50:55.520
because people eventually
need those things.

00:50:55.520 --> 00:51:00.530
If I called for boycott
of, say, apparels or shoes,

00:51:00.530 --> 00:51:01.670
it's not going to work.

00:51:01.670 --> 00:51:05.430
Maybe some people,
sentimentally or emotionally,

00:51:05.430 --> 00:51:08.572
ideally, they can be engaged
for a few days, or a few months,

00:51:08.572 --> 00:51:10.030
or a few years,
but eventually they

00:51:10.030 --> 00:51:12.210
will go to buy the product.

00:51:12.210 --> 00:51:17.690
So I was proposing that
consumers should demand a child

00:51:17.690 --> 00:51:20.100
labor fee carpet.

00:51:20.100 --> 00:51:22.640
And I have to find the answer.

00:51:22.640 --> 00:51:26.930
Of course, I took advise
from many good minds

00:51:26.930 --> 00:51:30.420
that how we can evolve a full
fledged monitoring and labeling

00:51:30.420 --> 00:51:34.170
system so that consumers
can find the solution.

00:51:34.170 --> 00:51:38.750
These children who
were withdrawn,

00:51:38.750 --> 00:51:42.860
they created jobs
for adult people.

00:51:42.860 --> 00:51:46.580
And the adult people were not
imported from other countries.

00:51:46.580 --> 00:51:50.022
All those adult people
were found locally.

00:51:50.022 --> 00:51:51.230
And they could find the jobs.

00:51:51.230 --> 00:51:56.140
So the parents were able to get
better employment opportunities

00:51:56.140 --> 00:51:57.390
in place of children.

00:51:57.390 --> 00:51:59.070
And these children
went to school.

00:51:59.070 --> 00:52:01.210
If they're not working
as child laborers

00:52:01.210 --> 00:52:03.520
and there's no other job
opportunities for them

00:52:03.520 --> 00:52:06.420
in that local area
of carpet production,

00:52:06.420 --> 00:52:08.150
then they have gone to school.

00:52:08.150 --> 00:52:10.350
And we did a regular followup.

00:52:10.350 --> 00:52:13.820
We have devised certain
databases, certain tracking

00:52:13.820 --> 00:52:15.280
systems.

00:52:15.280 --> 00:52:17.460
And most of the
children whom we free,

00:52:17.460 --> 00:52:19.730
right from the
identification and rescue

00:52:19.730 --> 00:52:23.280
operations to legal actions to
rehabilitation and education

00:52:23.280 --> 00:52:27.020
followup and so on,
that is also not enough.

00:52:27.020 --> 00:52:31.990
And that's why in the future
I would love to learn and take

00:52:31.990 --> 00:52:34.790
advice and cooperation
from Google

00:52:34.790 --> 00:52:38.360
to help us in devising
more concrete tracking

00:52:38.360 --> 00:52:43.510
systems, monitoring systems,
beside some kind of app

00:52:43.510 --> 00:52:46.230
of engaging people, which
I was suggesting before.

00:52:46.230 --> 00:52:47.684
Could be opportunities.

